./README.md:11:A GNOME Shell extension that adds a blur look to different parts of the GNOME Shell, including the top panel, dash and overview.
./README.md:13:[<img src="https://hosted.weblate.org/widgets/blur-my-shell/-/blur-my-shell/multi-auto.svg" align="right">](https://hosted.weblate.org/engage/blur-my-shell/)
./README.md:17:- apply a blur effect to different components of the shell:
./README.md:18:  - overview
./README.md:19:    - uses static blur only, [see here to understand what it means](#static-and-dynamic-blur)
./README.md:20:    - you can choose the colour of the components of the overview, to integrate them better with the background
./README.md:21:    - blurs the workspace separation too — useful with [Desktop Cube](https://extensions.gnome.org/extension/4648/desktop-cube/)
./README.md:23:    - you can choose between static blur and dynamic blur for the panel
./README.md:24:    - you can select the background of the panel itself (above the blur), to force transparency for example
./README.md:25:    - in the same settings, panel blur can be deactivated when a window is near it, for example in fullscreen
./README.md:26:    - you can deactivate the panel blur automatically when entering the overview if you need it
./README.md:28:    - you can choose between static blur and dynamic blur for Dash to Dock
./README.md:29:    - you can configure the background color of the dash itself for it not to interfere with the blur
./README.md:30:    - and you can deactivate the blur when entering the overview
./README.md:31:  - application folders background
./README.md:32:    - uses dynamic blur only
./README.md:33:    - you can select the styling of the background of the folder when it is opened
./README.md:35:    - uses static blur only
./README.md:36:  - popup blur
./README.md:37:    - you can choose between static blur and dynamic blur
./README.md:39:    - static and dynamic blur use the selected pipeline, like other surface components
./README.md:40:    - you can choose a transparent, light, dark, or automatic background above the blur
./README.md:41:    - popup blur has separate corner-radius settings for the different popup surface types
./README.md:42:    - rounded corners are handled by the extension
./README.md:43:  - lockscreen — to customize the already existing blur
./README.md:44:    - uses static blur only
./README.md:46:    - uses dynamic blur only
./README.md:48:    - you can choose between static blur and dynamic blur
./README.md:49:    - static blur:
./README.md:50:      - similar to the Windows “Mica” effect
./README.md:51:      - you select a pipeline, just like static blur for any other component
./README.md:52:      - **if you use multiple monitors, be aware that blur may not be handled properly**
./README.md:54:    - dynamic blur:
./README.md:55:      - similar to the Windows “Acrylic” effect
./README.md:58:    - you can select the opacity of the window that is above the blur: a lower opacity means it will be less legible; and a totally opaque setting can be used in pair with a transparent GTK theme to make the background of the windows blurred without touching at its content
./README.md:59:    - but you can choose to make the focused window totally opaque so that you can enjoy your blur while always having a legible window you work on!
./README.md:60:    - you can activate an option to better blur the windows while in overview, although it won't make the blur perfect
./README.md:61:    - and there are two modes for blurring applications:
./README.md:62:      - whitelisting (by default), where only windows that are selected are blurred
./README.md:63:      - blacklisting, where every window is blurred, excepted for the selected ones
./README.md:64:- preferences include a global blur profile on the Surfaces page; panel, Dash to Dock, popup blur, applications, and Window List can use that profile or keep their own local settings
./README.md:65:- the global profile controls blur type, pipeline, and the default background override style
./README.md:67:## Static and dynamic blur
./README.md:69:For the difference between static blur and dynamic blur:
./README.md:71:- static blur uses a static image of the wallpaper, and applies the effects that are part of a pipeline on it
./README.md:73:  - for each pipeline, you can add effects (including gaussian blur, Monte Carlo blur, pixelization, color, noise, luminosity... with more coming soon, you can open issues if you have a specific idea!), configure them, reorder and delete them
./README.md:74:  - the effects order is important: the first effect in list will be applied... first
./README.md:76:  - surface corner radius is configured from the Surfaces page, not as a pipeline effect
./README.md:77:  - even though it is static, this method of applying effects is not always so fast: for example, applying non-native gaussian blur, or Monte Carlo blur with a lot of iterations will make GNOME Shell quite slow while using the overview or switching workspace. This is being worked on, but for the moment you can for example limit yourself to 5 to 10 iterations for the Monte Carlo blur (which looks cool anyway!), and use native gaussian blur (which is very slightly less precise, but that really does not change anything in reality)
./README.md:78:- dynamic blur makes the component translucent, and samples what is directly behind it
./README.md:79:  - it uses the selected pipeline too: blur is only applied when the pipeline contains a blur effect
./README.md:80:  - pipelines without a blur effect can still use effects such as pixelization, color, noise, and luminosity on live content
./README.md:81:  - native dynamic blur stays on the optimized Shell path when possible; shader effects use a refreshed live snapshot so they can process real pixels
./README.md:82:  - rounded corners are applied by the extension on the blurred actor
./README.md:84:  - this method of blurring is not very efficient: even though it should not slow down your computer to a halt, using static blur is still preferred when possible
./README.md:85:  - dynamic blur can still show black-rectangle artifacts near the blurred surface; this is a GNOME Shell compositor limitation
./README.md:86:  - if that happens, you can enable “Disable clipped redraws” in the Other preferences tab; it usually fixes the artifacts, but slows down GNOME Shell globally, even when blur is hidden, so leave it off unless you need it
./README.md:90:Blur my Shell is guaranteed to be compatible, in the sense of at least not to mess around, with the following extensions:
./README.md:94:- [Multi Monitor Bar](https://extensions.gnome.org/extension/8773/multi-monitor-bar/) (the panel on each monitor is automatically blurred)
./README.md:98:- [Panel Corners](https://extensions.gnome.org/extension/4805/panel-corners/), with surface corners handled by Blur my Shell
./README.md:99:- [Burn my Windows](https://extensions.gnome.org//extension/4679/burn-my-windows/), although nothing is blurred either
